<div id="main_content">
	<h2>UCF and Irish Students Sharpen Global Technical Skills Through Virtual Project</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Zenaida Gonzalez Kotala
		
		<span class="date">Oct. 26, 2007</span></p>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:flammia@pegasus.cc.ucf.edu">Madelyn Flammia, UCF English</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-5654</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="index?page=article&amp;id=0024004107de59bdf0115d2e01442007a58"></a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>Eighteen college students on two continents are working together on a technical communications project that promises to teach them job skills necessary for success in a global society.<br />
<br />
Madelyn Flammia, an associate professor of English at the University of Central Florida, began the project last year when she had some of her students pair up with students at the University of Limerick in Ireland. Each team created Web sites that focused on cross-cultural communication. Flammia found that despite a few missteps, the students were successful.<br />
<br />
&ldquo;You could say they belonged to the technical communication (writing) culture and that was more powerful than their other cultural differences,&rdquo; Flammia said. <br />
<br />
This year another group of the professor&rsquo;s students are taking the project one step further. They are creating a single Web site for the University of Limerick to promote the technical communication program it offers. The students must also create brochures for the department, and they must target young Irish students.<br />
<br />
Those involved in the project are using teleconferencing, a virtual learning environment called Sulis, a real-time conferencing program called Skype and e-mail to communicate and the get the assignments done. They also are learning how to be sensitive to cultural differences.<br />
<br />
&ldquo;Learning to juggle different methods of communications and to work together with other cultures are key skills our future workforce will need to master in order to be successful,&rdquo; Flammia said. &ldquo;What the students on both continents are learning is invaluable. It will give them an edge in the global job market.&rdquo;<br />
<br />
The students have already met online and selected project leaders and designers. They expect to have finished products by the end of the semester.&nbsp; <br />
<br />
&ldquo;Virtual offices are becoming more common in business and academia,&rdquo; said 25-year-old Angela Hamilton, one of the students in Flammia&rsquo;s class. &ldquo;It's especially challenging for projects that require teamwork. Instead of sitting down together to bounce ideas off one another, one person is staring at a computer screen in the middle of the night while the other just got off work and is rushing to class, punching keys on their Blackberry five time zones away.&rdquo;<br />
<br />
Flammia teaches graduate and undergraduate courses in the Technical Communication Program. Most of her classes are online this year. She is also a faculty associate for the Office of International Studies. Her research interests include technical publication, document design, medical rhetoric and international technical communication. Most recently, she presented &ldquo;Student Experiences in Irish and U.S. Virtual Teams&rdquo; at the Society for Technical Communication's Annual Conference.<br />
<br />
The University of Limerick shares several similarities with UCF. Both focused on technology-related programs initially before becoming more comprehensive centers of higher learning. Both universities are also looking for partnerships and for ways to use technology to better serve a larger student population.<br />
<br />
Flammia plans to expand her class project next year to include another university from another culture, perhaps in Asia or Latin America.</p>
		
	
